 <div class="abstract" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
  <span class="label">Abstract</span>
  <p>Five species of the grass genus 
   <span class="italic">
    <div content-type="taxon-name" class="named-content">Spartina</div>
   </span> are invading salt marshes along the Pacific coast of North America, of which three have been documented in British Columbia, Canada, in only the last decade. A taxonomic synopsis of the two native (
   <span class="italic">
    <div content-type="taxon-name" class="named-content">Spartina gracilis</div>
   </span>, 
   <span class="italic">
    <div content-type="taxon-name" class="named-content">Spartina pectinata</div>
   </span>) and five introduced 
   <span class="italic">
    <div content-type="taxon-name" class="named-content">Spartina</div>
   </span> taxa (
   <span class="italic">
    <div content-type="taxon-name" class="named-content">Spartina anglica</div>
   </span>, 
   <span class="italic">
    <div content-type="taxon-name" class="named-content">Spartina alterniflora</div>
   </span>, 
   <span class="italic">
    <div content-type="taxon-name" class="named-content">Spartina densiflora</div>
   </span>, 
   <span class="italic">
    <div content-type="taxon-name" class="named-content">Spartina patens</div>
   </span>, 
   <span class="italic">
    <div content-type="taxon-name" class="named-content">Spartina ×townsendii</div>
   </span>) in the Pacific Northwest is presented to facilitate their identification, including nomenclature, a new taxonomic key, new descriptions for a subset of taxa, and representative specimens. 
   <span class="italic">
    <div content-type="taxon-name" class="named-content">Spartina ×townsendii</div>
   </span> is newly reported for the flora of British Columbia. The non-coastal species 
   <span class="italic">
    <div content-type="taxon-name" class="named-content">Spartina pectinata</div>
   </span> is reported from an urban site in British Columbia, the first confirmed report of the taxon for the province. Lectotypes are newly designated for 
   <span class="italic">
    <div content-type="taxon-name" class="named-content">Spartina anglica</div>
   </span> C.E. Hubb., 
   <span class="italic">
    <div content-type="taxon-name" class="named-content">Spartina maritima</div>
   </span> subvar. 
   <span class="italic">fallax</span> St.-Yves, and 
   <span class="italic">
    <div content-type="taxon-name" class="named-content">Spartina cynosuroides</div>
   </span> f. 
   <span class="italic">major</span> St.-Yves.
  </p>
